rophic isbn_clean regression. Evidence suggests source choice matters more than broad normalization here, and unnecessary normalization could regress valid parenthetical titles that the validation set genuinely keeps.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.01\n    }\n  ]\n}\n            \n            Compact summary from the prior reasoning:\n            {\n  "root_cause": "The dominant current failure is a regression caused by normalization/format handling, not blocking or entity matching. isbn_clean fell from 100% to 0% because the fused output now preserves 10-digit ISBN strings with leading zeroes while the validation set expects the canonical integer-like string without leading zeroes (e.g. 0618250743 -> 618250743). This is a pre-fusion representation mismatch. The genres errors are also pre-fusion/representation-driven relative to the validation format: validation stores a plain comma-separated string, while the pipeline/list handling is producing Python-list-style serialized values, causing systematic mismatches even when the underlying genre content is mostly right. Blocking/matching are not the bottleneck: correspondences exist, recall probes show no issue, and matching F1 is solid. Some remaining page_count/title/publisher gaps are fusion-choice or structural disagreements, but the highest-impact fix must first undo the normalization-format regressions.",\n  "next_step": "Routing must go to normalization_node because the needed fixes transform source values before fusion to match the validation set\\u2019s exact representation. The biggest impact attribute is isbn_clean (0% accuracy, previously 100%), and its errors are clearly systematic formatting differences, not wrong source choice. genres also shows target-format incompatibility: validation examples are comma-separated title-cased strings, while current outputs are serialized list objects. Protected attributes already above 85%\\u2014especially language (90%) and publish