res": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "publisher": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep",\n        "case": "title"\n      },\n      "page_count": {\n        "output_type": "int",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "publish_year": {\n        "output_type": "int",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  "list_columns": []\n}\n        {\n  "status": "success",\n  "attempt": 3,\n  "max_attempts": 3,\n  "validation_set": "input/datasets/books/testsets/validation_set.csv",\n  "llm_specs": {\n    "amazon_small": {},\n    "goodreads_small": {\n      "author": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "page_count": {\n        "output_type": "int",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "publish_year": {\n        "output_type": "int",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "publisher": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      }\n    },\n    "metabooks_small": {\n      "genres": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "publisher": {\n        "strip_whitespace": true,\n        "on_failure": "keep",\n        "case": "title"\n      },\n      "page_count": {\n        "output_type": "int",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      },\n      "publish_year": {\n        "output_type": "int",\n        "on_failure": "keep"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  "llm_list_columns": [],\n  "llm_reasoning": "Target style keeps title/author/language/publisher in original mixed case, stores publish_year and page_count as integers, and genres as a comma-separated string rather than a list object. IDs and isbn_clean were preserved per rules. To improve the low-accuracy fields, only minimal visible fixes were applied: cast numeric float years/pages to int, trim text whitespace, and title-case metabooks publisher because source shows inconsistent casing like \'Troll Communications Llc\' and \'HarperCollins\' while target publisher values are conventional title-style names.",\n  "datasets": {\n    "amazon_small": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260322_155058_books/normalization/attempt_2/amazon_small.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260322_155058_books/normalization/attempt_3/amazon_small.csv",\n      "row_count": 10000,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {},\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    },\n    "goodreads_small": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260322_155058_books/normalization/attempt_2/goodreads_small.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260322_155058_books/normalization/attempt_3/goodreads_small.csv",\n      "row_count": 10000,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "author": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "page_count": {\n          "output_type": "int",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publish_year": {\n          "output_type": "int",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publisher": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    },\n    "metabooks_small": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260322_155058_books/normalization/attempt_2/metabooks_small.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260322_155058_books/normalization/attempt_3/metabooks_small.csv",\n      "row_count": 10000,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "genres": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publisher": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep",\n          "case": "title"\n        },\n        "page_count": {\n          "output_type": "int",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publish_year": {\n          "output_type": "int",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    }\n  },\n  "warnings": [],\n  "acceptance_gate": {\n    "requested": false,\n    "request": {},\n    "pending": {}\n  },\n  "reverted_to_original": false,\n  "created_at": "2026-03-22T15:58:55.962237"\n}\n    \n        Create evaluation code that:\n        - Uses the correct fusion strategy\n        - Loads the fused output\n        - Loads the gold standard evaluation set (validation in sealed mode, otherwise test)\n        - Prints structured evaluation metrics\n        - Prints chosen evaluation functions in a compact one-line summary\n        - If helper modules are imported from local files (e.g., list_normalization), use a robust fallback import pattern that works from output/code execution context.\n        - Does NOT require exact matching everywhere by default.\n\n        EVALUATION ROBUSTNESS RULES (MANDATORY):\n- Use validation-set representation as the normalization target for evaluation.\n- Normalize fused and gold columns to the SAME representation before evaluating.\n- For country-like columns, infer and apply a shared normalize_country output_format from the evaluation set (alpha_2/alpha_3/numeric/name/official_name).\n- For free-text/list-like columns, avoid strict exact comparisons unless values are canonical identifiers.\n  Prefer tokenized_match with an explicit threshold (for example 0.7-0.9) instead of exact-only semantics.\n- If using set-based comparison on textual lists, first canonicalize list elements consistently across fused and gold.\n- Choose the right evaluation function per attribute type:\n  * tokenized_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates where only the year matters\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings (use reasonable tolerance)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent or all-null), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and meaningful in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n- IMPORTANT: When the gold set has a parent column (e.g. "tracks") but the fused output has sub-columns\n  derived from it (e.g. "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"),\n  DROP the sub-columns from evaluation unless they have explicit corresponding columns in the gold set.\n  Evaluating derived sub-columns against a non-existent gold column produces zero accuracy and wastes\n  investigation cycles. Only evaluate attributes that have a direct 1:1 column match in the gold set.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(float.is_integer).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, use fused_id_column="eval_id" (NOT "_id" or "id").\n  The eval_id column is pre-computed to map cluster IDs back to validation-set source IDs.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The dominant current failure is a regression caused by normalization/format handling, not blocking or entity matching. isbn_clean fell from 100% to 0% because the fused output now preserves 10-digit ISBN strings with leading zeroes while the validation set expects the canonical integer-like string without leading zeroes (e.g. 0618250743 -> 618250743). This is a pre-fusion representation mismatch. The genres errors are also pre-fusion/representation-driven relative to the validation format: validation stores a plain comma-separated string, while the pipeline/list handling is producing Python-list-style serialized values, causing systematic mismatches even when the underlying genre content is mostly right. Blocking/matching are not the bottleneck: correspondences exist, recall probes show no issue, and matching F1 is solid. Some remaining page_count/title/publisher gaps are fusion-choice or structural disagreements, but the highest-impact fix must first undo the normalization-format regressions.",\n  "next_node": "normalization_node",\n  "reasoning": "Routing must go to normalization_node because the needed fixes transform source values before fusion to match the validation set\\u2019s exact representation. The biggest impact attribute is isbn_clean (0% accuracy, previously 100%), and its errors are clearly systematic formatting differences, not wrong source choice. genres also shows target-format incompatibility: validation examples are comma-separated title-cased strings, while current outputs are serialized list objects. Protected attributes already above 85%\\u2014especially language (90%) and publish_year (100%)\\u2014should be preserved. Fusion changes for page_count/publisher/title can wait until after these normalization issues are fixed, because pipeline_adaption cannot safely repair leading-zero ISBN formatting or source string/list serialization mismatches.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "With current matching/blocking, a realistic ceiling remains around 79% overall. Fixing normalization should recover most of the lost isbn_clean accuracy and improve genres representation materially, likely yielding the largest immediate gain. Some page_count, title, and publisher errors are structurally limited by source disagreement, so perfect accuracy is unlikely without later fusion tuning; near-term post-normalization performance should move into the 70s.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "isbn_clean",\n      "issue": "Current fused values retain leading-zero 10-digit ISBN strings, but validation expects the same identifier without leading zeroes. This caused a catastrophic regression from 100% to 0% despite sources being otherwise aligned.",\n      "fix": "In normalization_node, standardize isbn_clean in all source datasets to the validation format by treating it as a string identifier, stripping whitespace/non-digit separators, and removing leading zeroes for 10-digit ISBN values so outputs match examples like 0618250743 -> 618250743. Preserve non-null values as strings, not numeric floats.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "This is not a resolver problem. Source-vs-validation shows high fuzzy agreement across all sources and mismatch samples are pure format issues. Any resolver would still emit the wrong representation if values are not normalized first. prefer_higher_trust is acceptable to keep after normalization because source choice is not the main error; voting/longest_string would not solve leading-zero mismatches.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.125\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "genres",\n      "issue": "Validation expects a plain comma-separated genre string in title case, but current pipeline output serializes genres in Python-list style, producing systematic representation mismatches. The content is often close, but the format is wrong for evaluation.",\n      "fix": "In normalization_node, ensure source genres remain or are converted to a flat comma-separated string matching validation style rather than list objects/stringified Python lists. Do not over-normalize into list cells before fusion. If source values are comma-delimited, keep atomic items trimmed and preserve title-style capitalization consistent with validation output.",\n   