"row_count": 10000,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "genres": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publisher": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep",\n          "case": "title"\n        },\n        "page_count": {\n          "output_type": "int",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publish_year": {\n          "output_type": "int",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    }\n  },\n  "warnings": [],\n  "acceptance_gate": {\n    "requested": false,\n    "request": {},\n    "pending": {}\n  },\n  "reverted_to_original": false,\n  "created_at": "2026-03-22T15:58:55.962237"\n}\n    \n        Create evaluation code that:\n        - Uses the correct fusion strategy\n        - Loads the fused output\n        - Loads the gold standard evaluation set (validation in sealed mode, otherwise test)\n        - Prints structured evaluation metrics\n        - Prints chosen evaluation functions in a compact one-line summary\n        - If helper modules are imported from local files (e.g., list_normalization), use a robust fallback import pattern that works from output/code execution context.\n        - Does NOT require exact matching everywhere by default.\n\n        EVALUATION ROBUSTNESS RULES (MANDATORY):\n- Use validation-set representation as the normalization target for evaluation.\n- Normalize fused and gold columns to the SAME representation before evaluating.\n- For country-like columns, infer and apply a shared normalize_country output_format from the evaluation set (alpha_2/alpha_3/numeric/name/official_name).\n- For free-text/list-like columns, avoid strict exact comparisons unless values are canonical identifiers.\n  Prefer tokenized_match with an explicit threshold (for example 0.7-0.9) instead of exact-only semantics.\n- If using set-based comparison on textual lists, first canonicalize list elements consistently across fused and gold.\n- Choose the right evaluation function per attribute type:\n  * tokenized_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates where only the year matters\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings (use reasonable tolerance)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent or all-null), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and meaningful in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n- IMPORTANT: When the gold set has a parent column (e.g. "tracks") but the fused output has sub-columns\n  derived from it (e.g. "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"),\n  DROP the sub-columns from evaluation unless they have explicit corresponding columns in the gold set.\n  Evaluating derived sub-columns against a non-existent gold column produces zero accuracy and wastes\n  investigation cycles. Only evaluate attributes that have a direct 1:1 column match in the gold set.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(float.is_integer).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, use fused_id_column="eval_id" (NOT "_id" or "id").\n  The eval_id column is pre-computed to map cluster IDs back to validation-set source IDs.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The main remaining errors are now in fusion strategy, not normalization, blocking, or matching. Blocking/matching are healthy (all correspondence files non-empty, F1 ~0.80-0.85, no recall issues), and the prior normalization regression on isbn_clean is already fixed/protected at 100%. The current pipeline is selecting the wrong source or wrong resolver for several low-performing attributes: genres uses most_complete even though validation expects complementary genres combined from goodreads+metabooks; publisher uses most_complete even though source-vs-validation shows metabooks is exact 100% and should be trusted; title and page_count trust maps are reversed, currently favoring amazon although amazon is the weakest source in the probe data. There is also a likely source-loading mismatch in code: the pipeline loads normalization/attempt_1 while the current normalized files are in attempt_3, which may explain some regressions, but under the routing rules the next fixable stage is fusion logic because blocking/matching are frozen-good and the dominant configurable errors are resolver/trust choices.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "Route to pipeline_adaption because the highest-impact remaining fixes are attribute fusers and trust maps. Do not touch protected attributes already >85%, especially publish_year and isbn_clean at 100%. genres is the top improvable attribute and needs union-style fusion to match validation provenance patterns like goodreads+metabooks. publisher, title, and page_count all show wrong source preference under current trust ordering. Although the code appears to load attempt_1 normalized files instead of attempt_3, the actionable next stage within the allowed routing is still fusion adaptation: change resolvers/trust maps and preserve working attributes. Normalization should not be revisited first because current mismatch examples for the priority attributes are mostly wrong value choice, not simple formatting, and isbn_clean is no longer broken.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "With current matching/blocking structure, overall accuracy around 0.80-0.85 appears realistic. The supplied ceiling estimate is 88.5%, but page_count/publisher/title are partly structurally limited by source disagreement, so a practical near-term target after fusion fixes is low 80s rather than perfect accuracy.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "genres",\n      "issue": "Current resolver most_complete picks a single source\'s longer genre string, but validation expects complementary genres combined across sources, typically goodreads_small + metabooks_small. This causes systematic under-recall and occasional missing values.",\n      "fix": "Change genres fuser from most_complete to union.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Validation samples explicitly show combined provenance (e.g. goodreads+metabooks), and mismatch examples show fused values are often strict subsets of expected values. Union best matches list-like complementary data. Voting would keep only shared/common values and lose recall; intersection would be even worse; prefer_higher_trust/favour_sources would choose one source and miss complementary genres. Because genres accuracy is only 30% and classified improvable with 100% ceiling, this is the clearest fusion fix.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.09\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "publisher",\n      "issue": "Current resolver most_complete chooses verbose/imprint variants like \'Simon & Schuster (Trade Division)\' or wrong imprints like \'Eos\', while validation usually wants the canonical publisher name. Probe data shows metabooks_small matches validation exactly in 100% of examined cases.",\n      "fix": "Change publisher fuser from most_complete to prefer_higher_trust with trust_map {\'metabooks_small\': 3.0, \'goodreads_small\': 2.0, \'amazon_small\': 1.0}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Source-vs-validation evidence is decisive: metabooks_small exact=100%, goodreads_small exact=67%, amazon_small exact=20%. prefer_higher_trust is therefore the best resolver. most_complete over-selects noisy longer publisher strings; longest_string would worsen that; voting can fail when amazon/goodreads agree on a non-canonical imprint. A strong trust preference for metabooks aligns with the validation provenance examples.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.05\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "title",\n      "issue": "Current title fuser prefer_higher_trust is configured backwards, favoring amazon_small, but probe data shows goodreads_small is the strongest source and amazon_small the weakest. This yields expanded/marketing titles instead of validation\'s canonical titles.",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for title but reverse trust_map to {\'goodreads_small\': 3.0, \'metabooks_small\': 2.0, \'amazon_small\': 1.0}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Probe comparison: goodreads_small exact=67%, metabooks_small exact=50%, amazon_small exact=30%, with fuzzy 100% for goodreads/metabooks. Validation often prefers canonical shorter title forms from goodreads, not amazon\'s embellished variants. shortest_string is tempting for some cases but would be brittle and could truncate legitimate parenthetical titles that validation keeps. prefer_higher_trust with corrected ordering best matches observed source quality while preserving existing behavior style.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.04\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "page_count",\n      "issue": "Current page_count fuser prefer_higher_trust is also reversed, favoring amazon_small even though amazon_small has 0% exact and 0% non-null in the probe sample. Validation often matches metabooks_small for page_count provenance.",\n      "fix": "Keep prefer_higher_trust for page_count but reverse trust_map to {\'metabooks_small\': 3.0, \'goodreads_small\': 2.0, \'amazon_small\': 1.0}.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "The evidence shows amazon_small is the worst source here, so current trust is actively harmful. maximum/median are not appropriate because page counts differ by edition and arithmetic aggregation can create values no source contains. voting is weak with only 2-3 sources and frequent disagreements. prefer_higher_trust toward metabooks is the safest improvement, though this attribute remains structurally limited.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.02\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "language",\n      "issue": "Language has regressed to 80% due to missing fused values, but it is near-protected and should not be over-tuned aggressively.",\n      "fix": "Preserve current resolver for language for now; if revisited later, test most_complete or prefer_higher_trust with metabooks-first only if missingness persists after broader fusion fixes.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Language is already relatively strong and not among the top-impact attributes. Unnecessary changes risk regressing a mostly working field. The current priority is genres/publisher/title/page_count.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.01\n    }\n  ]\n}\n            \n            Compact summary from the prior reasoning:\n            {\n  "root_cause": "The main remaining errors are now in fusion strategy, not normalization, blocking, or matching. Blocking/matching are healthy (all correspondence files non-empty, F1 ~0.80-0.85, no recall issues), and the prior normalization regression on isbn_clean is already fixed/protected at 100%. The current pipeline is selecting the wrong source or wrong resolver for several low-performing attributes: genres uses most_complete even though validation expects complementary